i>pōl</i> ‘pool, pond’ or perhaps <i>pull</i> ‘pool, creek’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Pulford IV was born about 1190, in Pulford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Robert de Pulford III, was 11188 and his mother, Jane de Polford, was 11. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Jane de Polford. He died after 1243, in his hometown."},"et":{"abt 1190–aft 1243":"umbes 1190–pärast 1243","1190–1243":"1190–1243","1180–1228":"1180–1228","1210–1290":"1210–1290","1214–1250":"1214–1250","1159–1159":"1159–1159","1228":"1228","1190":"1190","1214":"1214","1159":"1159","abt 1190":"umbes 1190","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","aft 1243":"pärast 1243","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","Pulford, Cheshire, England":"Pulford, Cheshire, England","Pulford Castle, Pulford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Pulford, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pulford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Pulford, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingd